(1, 2, 3, 'asset-management', 'Turkish State Railways (TCDD) Solar Power Plant is Monitored with PI System', 'Turkish State Railways (TCDD) Solar Power Plant is Monitored with PI System', 'Aiming to produce its own energy, TCDD built Solar Power Plant (SPP) on its own property in Selçuk, Izmir. TCDD chose to use OSIsoft PI System to display the data of 1MW Solar Power Plant it has built and to evaluate the collected data accurately.', 'Aiming to produce its own energy, **TCDD** built Solar Power Plant (SPP) on its own property in Selçuk, Izmir. TCDD chose to use OSIsoft PI System to display the data of 1MW Solar Power Plant it has built and to evaluate the collected data accurately.\n\nInformation received from **SPP** is sent to Alsancak Telecommand Center with **Radiolink** technology \n\n\nThe data and visual warnings displayed in real time were designed in the displays prepared using PI Vision so that operators can easily understand and interfere. In addition to the information obtained directly from the SPP site, the calculations and customized measurements which the operation team desired to monitor were also included in the displays.\n\n \n\nPI System is a system that allows monitoring the incoming data, customized measurements and calculations as well as reporting them as desired instantly. TCDD team is able to do performance analysis of the solar power plant\'s standard reports such as daily, monthly and yearly production and consumption data reports.\n\nPI System; in addition to monitoring, creating alarms and reporting, also has features such as providing e-mail alerts to operators, manual data entering to PI Server with devices such as user computers, tablets, hand held data loggers, and monitoring the data that is in the Server with these devices.\n\n**What is important for Solar and Wind power operations are,**\n\n*	Faulty turbine warnings\n*	Inverter failures and alarms\n*	Production trends\n*	Determination of underperformance\n*	Customizable performance calculations and measurements\n*	Performance analysis\n*	Comprehensive evaluation of fleet-wide data\n*	Standard reports that can be generated efficiently by the operation team\n*	Monitoring images that can be designed as desired\n*	Clear visual warnings for operators\n*	It is possible to provide many details such as problem identification and monitoring, faster and wiser decisions with PI System. Contact us for more information (mail link).\n', 'blog_posts\\September2019\\nZNC4cARgpko16OFJYcO.jpg', 'turkish-state-railways-tcdd-solar-power-plant-is-monitored-with-pi-system', 'dde', 'DRAFT', '1', '2019-09-10 13:04:47', '2020-01-30 05:52:59', 'Turkish State Railways (TCDD) Solar Power Plant is Monitored with PI System', '[\"Asset Management\",\"Industry 4.0\",\"Internet of Things\",\"Kontrolmatik\",\"SCADA\"]', NULL, 'en', ''),
(2, 1, 4, 'award', 'Kontrolmatik Named 44th Largest System Integrator Worldwide', 'Kontrolmatik Named 44th Largest System Integrator Worldwide', 'Kontrolmatik has been named the 44th largest System Integrator in the world by Control Engineering, according to their just-released System', 'Kontrolmatik has been named the 44th largest System Integrator in the world by Control Engineering, according to their just-released System Integrator Giants 2019 list.\n\nCFE Media has released its 2019 System Integrator Giants listing, which ranks the top global companies involved in system integration projects throughout manufacturing. Kontrolmatik has consecutively ranked top 44 out of the 100 system integrators distinguished by this award which were recognized in the annual Global System Integrator Report, and online at controleng.com and plantengineering.com\n\nKontrolmatik is honored to be included on the System Integrator Giants 2019 list, especially as we have risen up from last year’s 52nd position. From the list of candidates published, it was a real proud to know Kontrolmatik is one of the youngest companies in the candidates.\n\nKontrolmatik is a well known company in **Power Generation, Power Transmission, Oil&Gas, Petrochemistry, Process, Steel and Transportation.**\n\nAs one of the vendor-independent automation integration company in Turkey, Kontrolmatik provides a single source of responsibility for turn-key automation, instrumentation and electrical projects involving all major technologies. Kontrolmatik specialized in delivering fully integrated life-cycle solutions in the industrial instrumentation, controls and electrical (ICE) disciplines. This includes all phases of a project from Engineering through Fabrication, Construction, Commissioning and Maintenance.\n\nThank’s to dynamism and experience of our team at Kontrolmatik have challenged and executed local and international projects with great success. Up to now, we have executed and delivered projects in more than 20 different countries including Turkmenistan, Ethiopia, Afghanistan, Libya etc.\n\n**For more information get in contact with Kontrolmatik now!**\n\nReach the full list here: https://www.cfemedia.com/news/system-integrator-giants-2019/', 'blog_posts\\September2019\\PUAD7KZJC3dt81H50O2r.jpg', 'kontrolmatik-named-44th-largest-system-integrator-worldwide', 'Kontrolmatik Named 44th Largest System Integrator Worldwide', 'DRAFT', '1', '2019-09-10 13:24:31', '2019-09-10 13:24:31', 'Kontrolmatik Named 44th Largest System Integrator Worldwide', '[\"Award\",\"\\u00d6d\\u00fcl\"]', NULL, 'en', ''),
(3, 2, 8, 'endustri-4.0', 'LoRaWAN Technology', 'LoRaWAN Technology', 'If you are looking for a common protocol that enables your smart devices and IoT (Internet of Things) devices to communicate with each other, LoRaWAN™ is a great option for you. LoRaWAN ™ is optimized to use very little power and have long-range (LoRa),', 'If you are looking for a common protocol that enables your smart devices and IoT (Internet of Things) devices to communicate with each other, LoRaWAN™ is a great option for you. LoRaWAN ™ is optimized to use very little power and have long-range (LoRa), wide area network (WAN) features. Thus, LoRaWAN ™ provides a perfect solution for wireless and battery-powered end points within the IoT network. It can securely handle two-way communications by providing a data rate from 0.3 kbps to 50 kbps.\n\nIdeal applications for LoRaWAN ™ can be listed as sensor networks, security systems, smart home, smart measurement, industrial control and smart cities. Amsterdam is the first city to create IoT data network using 10 gateways with massive funding to ensure full coverage with LoRaWAN™.\n\nThanks to the adaptive data rate scheme, it is possible to achieve communication ranges of up to 2-5km in the city or up to 15km outside the city by balancing in between the communication range and messaging time in a wide spectrum at frequencies below GHz. LoRaWAN ™ operates in a multi-star topology, where gateways provide a transparent bridge for message exchange between end points and network center or cloud.\n\nGateways, which are typically electrically powered devices; it communicates with the end points via the LoRaWAN™ protocol before transmitting messages through traditional protocols such as Ethernet, 3G or Wi-Fi. Most end point communications are bidirectional, but they support LoRaWAN™ multicasting for network updates or distributed emergency bulk messages.\n\nThis function is especially useful for LoRaWAN™ application in flood systems. In an area where flooding is possible, an early warning system can be provided to the effected residents through a network of sensors.\n\n\n\nSmart Cities\n \n\n\n\nLoRaWAN offers an end-to-end, integrated, city-managed smart city infrastructure. Thanks to this infrastructure, a city can use many smart applications at the same time.\n\nMost of the sensor infrastructure that smart cities need is low power data communication and battery-isolated systems. When such systems are supported by a city-wide wireless network, a system, which has very low cost, works city-wide and that belongs to the city similar to IT infrastructure rises.\n\nIn this way, in contrast to what other telecom companies offer, an infrastructure of internet of things that city administrations can stretch as they wish is brought into the city without high communication costs, and with very low total operating costs.\n\n- Smart Street Lighting\n- Smart Car Parking System\n- Smart Environmental Management\n- Smart Waste Collection\n- Smart Energy Management\n- Smart Meter Reading\n\n \n\nSmart Tracking\nIndustry 4.0LoRaWAN makes a low cost, reliable and secure flexible sensor infrastructure available for the use of industry in the most clear and reliable way possible. It brings industry 4.0 to the factory and production facilities by providing remote monitoring of the existing machinery park.\n \n\n\n\nLoRaWAN makes a low cost, reliable and secure flexible sensor infrastructure available for the use of industry in the most clear and reliable way possible. It brings industry 4.0 to the factory and production facilities by providing remote monitoring of the existing machinery park.\n\nThanks to the company\'s extensive knowledge of MODBUS integration, it enables the data of the machines which are ready for PLC-based MODBUS integration running on the existing production line to be wirelessly transmitted to the internet; tracking and analysis of the extracted data can be performed, and this way condition monitoring of the machines and necessary improvements can be made.\n\nBy integrating these data into different databases or platforms with different methods when required, situational decision-making mechanisms can be established via integrated production tracking, smart algorithms; in this way the Industry 4.0 chain is completed very practically and with a very low cost.\n\nIn addition to PLC integration, monitoring of energy consumption of machines, temperature and humidity monitoring, vibration and motion monitoring, monitoring of contactors and other equipment can be followed by status monitoring.\n\n \n\n \n\nAgriculture\n \n\n\n\nLoRaWAN\'s ability to simultaneously provide wireless network technology and long-life low-cost sensors brings flexible solutions to key problems such as irrigation control, microclimate control, energy and machine management in agriculture.\n\nThe flexibility of this technology enables practical and cost-effective implementation of end-to-end solutions in agriculture. A low-cost gateway can monitor and control soil, air, machinery and energy from sensors in fields and greenhouses 15 km away. At the same time, thanks to the agricultural macro data and web services integrated to LoRaWAN IoT platform, it is possible to make decisions by using critical temperature and humidity data in the light of agricultural information about plants, and control irrigation efficiency and disease risk.\n\n \n\n \n\n \n\nSmart Networks\n \n\n\n\nThanks to low cost, low data transmission applications such as meter reading, monitoring of the basic parameters of the networks, and monitoring of power cuts, our company offers low cost smart network applications.\n\nRemote meter reading systems (OSOS) can be configured flexibly for electricity, water, gas and calorimeter both indoors and outdoors. With the low battery consumption and easy integration infrastructure of LoRaWAN technology, interfaces such as RS485, Optical, Pulse on the meters installed in field can be equipped with terminal units, readings can be handled from ranges such as 5-7 km in open areas, 500-1000 m in indoor areas and in between 8-10 floors.\n\nIn addition, energy analyzers for electricity and other measurement equipment with MODBUS integration, terminal units connected to devices that are capable of MODBUS integration or pulse integration on water, natural gas and heat networks provide remote monitoring of these networks, \nmonitoring with user-specific network and software integration of cuts and other network parameters with low costs.', NULL, 'lorawan-technology', 'LoRaWAN Technology', 'DRAFT', 'LoRaWAN Technology', '2019-09-10 13:28:35', '2020-01-31 05:43:26', 'LoRaWAN Technology', '[]', NULL, 'en', ''),
(4, 2, 13, 'industry-4.0', '21 Steps to Provide Cyber Security of SCADA Networks', '21 Steps to Provide Cyber Security of SCADA Networks', 'SCADA networks are involved in almost all critical infrastructures (electricity, natural gas, water, transport', 'SCADA networks are involved in almost all critical infrastructures (electricity, natural gas, water, transportation, health, etc.) that support our daily lives. As in other networks; modern servers, computers, switches/routers and applications are used in SCADA networks. With this modern infrastructure, while providing communication and monitoring of the points that are quite distant from one another; at the same time, potential security gaps may occur.\nSince SCADA networks are designed to be based on more efficiency and functionality, potential security gaps often may not be evaluated. Therefore, as cyber security, these networks can be weak and can lead to bad results such as undesirable service disconnections, or even complete loss of service in the event of a potential attack.\nIn 2001, with the work initiated by the US Ministry of Energy, the following 21 steps were proposed to improve the security of SCADA networks. The original English version of the document can be found here.\nIdentify all connections in the SCADA network.\n	Intranet, WAN and Business networks\n	Internet connections\n	Wireless connections (Access Point, Satellite connections, etc.)\n	Modem or dial-up connections\n	To business partners, suppliers or regulative connections  Remove any unnecessary connections from the SCADA network. \n	The connection to each network is potentially risky, so you must always isolate unnecessary connections from your SCADA network (DMZ can also be used). Review the remaining SCADA connections and ensure that the necessary reinforcements have been made.\n	Reports on the status of your SCADA network should be obtained through security risk analyzes and penetration tests, and the necessary solutions (IDS/IPS, FW, etc.) should be implemented. Stop applications and services that do not need to be used on the SCADA network.\n	the services which are not needed to be used continuously in SCADA network such as e-mail, internet access, remote access services should be stopped, and their access should be denied. Do not rely on SCADA Protocols to secure your network. Security should not only be implemented with SCADA protocols; many SCADA protocols cannot provide a real security. Follow the safety definitions recommended by the device and system manufacturers for their products.\n	Older devices do not have such configurations, but newer devices have security applications (SSL access, User Management, Log management, etc.). * If security configurations are supported according to the status of your assets, apply these configurations with support from your supplier. Take control of the accounts and devices that can be used as backdoor.\n	Many manufacturers may have accounts on their devices to provide private access, and these accounts must be found, and their access rights must be checked. Place intrusion detection and prevention systems (IDS / IPS) inside and outside of your network and provide 24/7 monitoring of the network.\n	With IDS systems, monitor the transactions of your SCADA network continuously so that abnormal or malicious transactions can be detected as soon as possible. Perform periodical technical inspections for your SCADA network, your corporate network, and other connected networks.\n	System and Network Administrators should regularly perform network and system checks using the required technical control software. Perform inspections at central and remote sites to measure and ensure the reliability of physical access.\n	Check that the physical environments in which all devices that make up the SCADA network are located are closed to unauthorized access. Train or build your team to analyze and detect attacks on the SCADA network.\n	With a team of experts in SCADA networks, ensure that threats are recognized and prevented as soon as possible. Identify Cyber Security duties, responsibilities, and user authorizations clearly and perceptibly.\n	The whole organization needs to be informed about cyber security, duties should be identified, and accesses should be configured. Document network architecture and identify your systems which hold critical or valuable information.\n	Always keep your documentation up-to-date in terms of visibility and knowledge management of the entire SCADA network. Create an attentive and sustainable risk management process.\n	Create an effective security and risk management process that the entire organization can follow. Create an in-depth protection strategy for your network (defense-in-depth principle).\n	Review all access and authorization rules. Build your protection strategy in depth as a Physical-Network-End point. Define cyber security requirements.\n	Create your rules and procedures with a cyber security program. Define duties and responsibilities in your organization and follow your procedures regularly. Create an effective configuration management process.\n	Create a configuration management process to keep your network and device configurations constantly up to date and under control. Perform periodical internal audits.\n	Control your security with internal audits as a part of your cyber security procedures. Create system backups and recovery plans.\n	Create backup and recovery plans to compensate for potential system and service loss as soon as possible. As top management identify performance criteria and responsible persons for Cyber Security.\n	Define your expectations from cyber security in line with the objectives of your organization. Establish internal rules for the security of the SCADA network and systems, and increase the level of knowledge of the organization regarding the subject through internal trainings.\n	Organize internal trainings to constantly keep your organization\'s level of knowledge and cyber security procedures up-to-date and maintain awareness.\n', NULL, '21-steps-to-provide-cyber-security-of-scada-networks4', '21 Steps to Provide Cyber Security of SCADA Networks', 'PUBLISHED', '0', '2019-09-09 05:15:57', '2020-01-31 07:15:31', NULL, '[]', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'en', '[]'),
(5, 2, 14, 'internet-of-things', '21 Steps to Provide Cyber Security of SCADA Networks', '21 Steps to Provide Cyber Security of SCADA Networks', 'SCADA networks are involved in almost all critical infrastructures (electricity, natural gas, water, tran', 'SCADA networks are involved in almost all critical infrastructures (electricity, natural gas, water, transportation, health, etc.) that support our daily lives. As in other networks; modern servers, computers, switches/routers and applications are used in SCADA networks. With this modern infrastructure, while providing communication and monitoring of the points that are quite distant from one another; at the same time, potential security gaps may occur.\nSince SCADA networks are designed to be based on more efficiency and functionality, potential security gaps often may not be evaluated. Therefore, as cyber security, these networks can be weak and can lead to bad results such as undesirable service disconnections, or even complete loss of service in the event of a potential attack.\nIn 2001, with the work initiated by the US Ministry of Energy, the following 21 steps were proposed to improve the security of SCADA networks. The original English version of the document can be found here.\nIdentify all connections in the SCADA network.\n	Intranet, WAN and Business networks\n	Internet connections\n	Wireless connections (Access Point, Satellite connections, etc.)\n	Modem or dial-up connections\n	To business partners, suppliers or regulative connections  Remove any unnecessary connections from the SCADA network. \n	The connection to each network is potentially risky, so you must always isolate unnecessary connections from your SCADA network (DMZ can also be used). Review the remaining SCADA connections and ensure that the necessary reinforcements have been made.\n	Reports on the status of your SCADA network should be obtained through security risk analyzes and penetration tests, and the necessary solutions (IDS/IPS, FW, etc.) should be implemented. Stop applications and services that do not need to be used on the SCADA network.\n	the services which are not needed to be used continuously in SCADA network such as e-mail, internet access, remote access services should be stopped, and their access should be denied. Do not rely on SCADA Protocols to secure your network. Security should not only be implemented with SCADA protocols; many SCADA protocols cannot provide a real security. Follow the safety definitions recommended by the device and system manufacturers for their products.\n	Older devices do not have such configurations, but newer devices have security applications (SSL access, User Management, Log management, etc.). * If security configurations are supported according to the status of your assets, apply these configurations with support from your supplier. Take control of the accounts and devices that can be used as backdoor.\n	Many manufacturers may have accounts on their devices to provide private access, and these accounts must be found, and their access rights must be checked. Place intrusion detection and prevention systems (IDS / IPS) inside and outside of your network and provide 24/7 monitoring of the network.\n	With IDS systems, monitor the transactions of your SCADA network continuously so that abnormal or malicious transactions can be detected as soon as possible. Perform periodical technical inspections for your SCADA network, your corporate network, and other connected networks.\n	System and Network Administrators should regularly perform network and system checks using the required technical control software. Perform inspections at central and remote sites to measure and ensure the reliability of physical access.\n	Check that the physical environments in which all devices that make up the SCADA network are located are closed to unauthorized access. Train or build your team to analyze and detect attacks on the SCADA network.\n	With a team of experts in SCADA networks, ensure that threats are recognized and prevented as soon as possible. Identify Cyber Security duties, responsibilities, and user authorizations clearly and perceptibly.\n	The whole organization needs to be informed about cyber security, duties should be identified, and accesses should be configured. Document network architecture and identify your systems which hold critical or valuable information.\n	Always keep your documentation up-to-date in terms of visibility and knowledge management of the entire SCADA network. Create an attentive and sustainable risk management process.\n	Create an effective security and risk management process that the entire organization can follow. Create an in-depth protection strategy for your network (defense-in-depth principle).\n	Review all access and authorization rules. Build your protection strategy in depth as a Physical-Network-End point. Define cyber security requirements.\n	Create your rules and procedures with a cyber security program. Define duties and responsibilities in your organization and follow your procedures regularly. Create an effective configuration management process.\n	Create a configuration management process to keep your network and device configurations constantly up to date and under control. Perform periodical internal audits.\n	Control your security with internal audits as a part of your cyber security procedures. Create system backups and recovery plans.\n	Create backup and recovery plans to compensate for potential system and service loss as soon as possible. As top management identify performance criteria and responsible persons for Cyber Security.\n	Define your expectations from cyber security in line with the objectives of your organization. Establish internal rules for the security of the SCADA network and systems, and increase the level of knowledge of the organization regarding the subject through internal trainings.\n	Organize internal trainings to constantly keep your organization\'s level of knowledge and cyber security procedures up-to-date and maintain awareness.\n', NULL, '21-steps-to-provide-cyber-security-of-scada-networks3', '21 Steps to Provide Cyber Security of SCADA Networks', 'PUBLISHED', '0', '2019-09-09 05:15:57', '2020-01-31 07:14:49', NULL, '[]', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'en', '[]'),
(6, 2, 18, 'network', '21 Steps to Provide Cyber Security of SCADA Networks', '21 Steps to Provide Cyber Security of SCADA Networks', 'SCADA networks are involved in almost all critical infrastructures (electricity, natural gas, water', 'SCADA networks are involved in almost all critical infrastructures (electricity, natural gas, water, transportation, health, etc.) that support our daily lives. As in other networks; modern servers, computers, switches/routers and applications are used in SCADA networks. With this modern infrastructure, while providing communication and monitoring of the points that are quite distant from one another; at the same time, potential security gaps may occur.\nSince SCADA networks are designed to be based on more efficiency and functionality, potential security gaps often may not be evaluated. Therefore, as cyber security, these networks can be weak and can lead to bad results such as undesirable service disconnections, or even complete loss of service in the event of a potential attack.\nIn 2001, with the work initiated by the US Ministry of Energy, the following 21 steps were proposed to improve the security of SCADA networks. The original English version of the document can be found here.\nIdentify all connections in the SCADA network.\n	Intranet, WAN and Business networks\n	Internet connections\n	Wireless connections (Access Point, Satellite connections, etc.)\n	Modem or dial-up connections\n	To business partners, suppliers or regulative connections  Remove any unnecessary connections from the SCADA network. \n	The connection to each network is potentially risky, so you must always isolate unnecessary connections from your SCADA network (DMZ can also be used). Review the remaining SCADA connections and ensure that the necessary reinforcements have been made.\n	Reports on the status of your SCADA network should be obtained through security risk analyzes and penetration tests, and the necessary solutions (IDS/IPS, FW, etc.) should be implemented. Stop applications and services that do not need to be used on the SCADA network.\n	the services which are not needed to be used continuously in SCADA network such as e-mail, internet access, remote access services should be stopped, and their access should be denied. Do not rely on SCADA Protocols to secure your network. Security should not only be implemented with SCADA protocols; many SCADA protocols cannot provide a real security. Follow the safety definitions recommended by the device and system manufacturers for their products.\n	Older devices do not have such configurations, but newer devices have security applications (SSL access, User Management, Log management, etc.). * If security configurations are supported according to the status of your assets, apply these configurations with support from your supplier. Take control of the accounts and devices that can be used as backdoor.\n	Many manufacturers may have accounts on their devices to provide private access, and these accounts must be found, and their access rights must be checked. Place intrusion detection and prevention systems (IDS / IPS) inside and outside of your network and provide 24/7 monitoring of the network.\n	With IDS systems, monitor the transactions of your SCADA network continuously so that abnormal or malicious transactions can be detected as soon as possible. Perform periodical technical inspections for your SCADA network, your corporate network, and other connected networks.\n	System and Network Administrators should regularly perform network and system checks using the required technical control software. Perform inspections at central and remote sites to measure and ensure the reliability of physical access.\n	Check that the physical environments in which all devices that make up the SCADA network are located are closed to unauthorized access. Train or build your team to analyze and detect attacks on the SCADA network.\n	With a team of experts in SCADA networks, ensure that threats are recognized and prevented as soon as possible. Identify Cyber Security duties, responsibilities, and user authorizations clearly and perceptibly.\n	The whole organization needs to be informed about cyber security, duties should be identified, and accesses should be configured. Document network architecture and identify your systems which hold critical or valuable information.\n	Always keep your documentation up-to-date in terms of visibility and knowledge management of the entire SCADA network. Create an attentive and sustainable risk management process.\n	Create an effective security and risk management process that the entire organization can follow. Create an in-depth protection strategy for your network (defense-in-depth principle).\n	Review all access and authorization rules. Build your protection strategy in depth as a Physical-Network-End point. Define cyber security requirements.\n	Create your rules and procedures with a cyber security program. Define duties and responsibilities in your organization and follow your procedures regularly. Create an effective configuration management process.\n	Create a configuration management process to keep your network and device configurations constantly up to date and under control. Perform periodical internal audits.\n	Control your security with internal audits as a part of your cyber security procedures. Create system backups and recovery plans.\n	Create backup and recovery plans to compensate for potential system and service loss as soon as possible. As top management identify performance criteria and responsible persons for Cyber Security.\n	Define your expectations from cyber security in line with the objectives of your organization. Establish internal rules for the security of the SCADA network and systems, and increase the level of knowledge of the organization regarding the subject through internal trainings.\n	Organize internal trainings to constantly keep your organization\'s level of knowledge and cyber security procedures up-to-date and maintain awareness.\n \n', NULL, '21-steps-to-provide-cyber-security-of-scada-networks2', '21 Steps to Provide Cyber Security of SCADA Networks', 'PUBLISHED', '0', '2019-09-09 05:15:57', '2020-01-31 07:13:59', NULL, '[]', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'en', '[]'),
