(13, 2, 5, 'cyber-security', 'Reduce OT Cyber Threat Risk with ICS Network Visualization and Asset Inventory', 'Reduce OT Cyber Threat Risk with ICS Network Visualization and Asset Inventory', 'Convergence of information technologies (IT) and operational technologies (OT), OT being more connected to external networks, and the spread of industrial IoT devices help to increase the efficiency of industrial processes. However, these trends bring risks and security gaps. This causes institutions to feel insecure. ', 'Convergence of information technologies (IT) and operational technologies (OT), OT being more connected to external networks, and the spread of industrial IoT devices help to increase the efficiency of industrial processes. However, these trends bring risks and security gaps. This causes institutions to feel insecure. 77% of companies believe they may be the target of a cyber security case related to industrial control systems.\n\nIt is clear that industrial cyber threats are the most important concern for managers. CISO (Chief Information Security Officers) are looking for ways to assess and manage risks within the OT. But in fact, CISO staff does not have enough data to overcome cyber security and operational risks of ICS (Industrial Control System).  \nIn order to assess and manage risks, it is necessary to know when and how the cyber security network, assets and businesses are changing. Until recently, the tools available to easily visualize and document the industrial network were scarce and inaccessible.\n\nNozomi Networks, with SCADAguardian , offers industrial network monitoring technology that enables you to monitor your networks in real time in a completely passive manner and overcome the challenges posed by current asset inventories. \n\nNetwork Visualization Increases Situational Awareness and Resolution Speed\nPassive industrial network monitoring tools work by connecting to a SPAN or mirror port of a switch or router and analysing the communication within the network. In this sense, SCADAguardian offers an easy-to-implement integration solution that eliminates process risk.\nWhen the installation is complete, SCADAguardian starts analyzing the ICS network traffic and creates an interactive visualization. We are confident that a comprehensive system visibility at this level will change the minds of managers about OT management risk. When operators and cyber security personnel begin to analyse the system, they often realize that there are network nodes or IP addresses in system which they are not aware of.\n\nWith SCADAguardian, you can quickly access a large amount of useful information, \n\n	Macro view of an industrial control network including all assets and end points having IP or MAC address, communicating on the network,\n	Devices that do not have an IP address communicating on layer 2 of the OSI model,\n	Subnets, protocols used to communicate between subnets, and network topologies of VLANs,\n	Nodes and protocols used to communicate between these nodes,\n	Map of all network connections including session and connections,\n	Ability to view any end point or connection to see detailed attributes,\n	Network traffic information such as workflow, protocols, and open TCP connections,\n	Printable and openable versions of network structure and details in multiple file formats.\n\nNode topology visualization within the network, provided by SCADAguardian.\n\nA Quick and Easy Way to Inventory Your ICS \nDeveloping and maintaining a central OT system inventory is a very difficult and time-consuming project. Another key security solution provided by SCADAguardian is automated asset inventory.\nCustom asset views facilitate visualization, finding and elaboration of asset information. SCADAguardian has 3 different functional visualization options.\n\nThese are;\n\nVisual grouping based on the Purdue model, list view and detailed, single asset views.\nWhile SCADAguardian lists common industrial devices, it also shows detailed information such as device name, type, serial number, product software version, product name and components of the devices it lists. SCADAguardian keeps this information up-to-date by identifying their assets in a non-intrusive way and updates them in real time.\n\nSCADAguardian also captures contexts such as how each device is being used. For example, it notices that a Cisco key (as indicated by its MAC address) is used as a Siemens Scalence Key (PROD vendor). This important feature leads to lower faulty warnings in abnormality detection and security gap identification compared to products that recognize coverage systems. Changes in hardware, software and devices are sent via warnings to bring potential cyber events or process risks to the attention of appropriate personnel.\n\nNozomi Networks solution provides complete visibility of OT networks together with risk causes. Network visualization panels and automated asset inventory provide the basic information needed to accurately identify and correct ICS cyber security risks.\n\n** SCADAguardian ** also combines information from many industrial areas into a single monitoring toolkit and provides a common platform to facilitate IT / OT convergence.\nIf you are concerned about the risk of OT cyber attacks, contact us to learn how SCADAguardian improves your organization\'s operational visibility, how it can reduce cyber risks and improve reliability. (mail link)\n', 'blog_posts\\September2019\\2176ZoiRDDdNv1x54ShQ.jpg', 'reduce-ot-cyber-threat-risk-with-ics-network-visualization-and-asset-inventory', 'Reduce OT Cyber Threat Risk with ICS Network Visualization and Asset Inventory', 'DRAFT', '0', '2019-09-12 09:24:02', '2020-01-31 06:49:31', 'Reduce OT Cyber Threat Risk with ICS Network Visualization and Asset Inventory', '[]', NULL, 'en', ''),
(14, 1, 15, 'kontrolmatik', 'OSIsoft PI System: Monitoring and Managing Energy', 'OSIsoft PI System: Monitoring and Managing Energy', 'Energy is one of the largest and most compulsory operational expenses for many organizations. Marginal reductions in energy consumption can significantly affect costs.', '**Energy Management with PI System**\r\n\r\n\r\nEnergy is one of the largest and most compulsory operational expenses for many organizations. Marginal reductions in energy consumption can significantly affect costs. Although many companies embark on energy initiatives, they fail due to lack of visibility in energy consumption, insufficiency of core values, and inability to measure the benefits of energy reduction initiatives. The PI System developed by OSIsoft helps organizations understand their energy networks, basic energy consumption, create Energy Performance Indicators and identify the impacts of energy initiatives. This article summarizes how organizations can use the PI System to capture energy measurements to provide real-time and historical visibility in energy use. This allows you to base the energy use throughout your organization and provides an understanding of the impacts of your energy initiatives.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n**Energy Management and ISO 50001**\r\n\r\nEnergy is a critical component for organizations and potentially a significant operating cost. One of the current standards for energy management is ISO 50001. Many organizations have adopted (or began to adopt) this standard in energy management to reduce energy costs as part of their corporate sustainability initiatives. Compliance with environmental policies or minimizing, the impact of their company on society. An inseparable part of the ISO 50001 standard is to base the energy use, efficiency and consumption, and then determine whether energy performance matches the defined objectives, and to continuously monitor and measure the processes to report the results. The PI System is well suited to help organizations meet these requirements.\r\n\r\n**With the PI System, companies can handle the followings:**\r\n\r\nCollect and consolidate energy data from assets, meters and external systems with an accuracy that provides the visibility required to evaluate energy performance. Create analytics to regulate energy data, and to monitor and measure energy performance. Provide powerful tools to analyze and share energy performance information. PI System information can be presented to users in a variety of ways and shared with other corporate systems. Planning phase of Top Level Solution ISO framework requires an energy audit to measure existing energy performance and identify gaps. This step is crucial for understanding which energy information are available in your organization. In many cases, additional measurement is required to achieve the correct level of detail to meet your energy reduction objectives. However, not performing measurement should not prevent organizations from collecting, modeling of current energy information; and collecting EnPIs for identification. Although this blog does not cover data collection, it should be noted that OSIsoft offers various initiatives and connectors to collect information from SCADA, PLC, DCS, meters, and many other data sources. Understanding energy use on one site and across your organization can add value to your organization, including below:\r\n\r\n*	Reduction of energy through process improvements.\r\n*	Detection of energy increases.\r\n*	Producing EnPIs such as kWh / ton or kWh / product.\r\n*	comparison of specific energy consumption between technologies.\r\n* Comparing the bill counter according to actual and calculated energy usage.\r\n*	Modeling the Energy Performance\r\n*	The first step in designing a model for energy management is to understand the relationships between your equipment / assets, your processing area and your overall organizational hierarchy. For this purpose, organizations can follow ISA 88 / ISA 95 standards to ensure consistency of terminology, definitions, process models etc. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAlternatively, organizations can develop their own models to configure energy performance data. In both cases, the hierarchy must be sufficiently detailed to capture all available energy performance information. To facilitate the maintenance and distribution of your model and related templates, it is essential to use a standard to improve your hierarchy.\r\nFigure 1 shows a PI AF model centered around energy. It shows a typical hierarchy that starts at the business level and goes down to the equipment level. This hierarchy provides visibility of energy performance from a high-level organizational overview to individual assets. In addition, the model enables its performance that gets the energy from equipment to be converted into a site and then into process areas till the establishment. In this example, energy information from assets is captured and recorded in real time, and Asset Analytics is used to calculate hourly, daily and monthly energy consumption and costs.\r\n\r\n\r\n**Visualization and Reporting**\r\nOnce the energy data is captured and the analysis is configured to create EnPIs of the analysis, the next step is to make sure that people in your company can access them in any way that gives them the most value. To this end, the PI System includes a range of analysis, visualization and integration capabilities. Consider the following scenarios:\r\n\r\nUsers who need to generate weekly or monthly reports to monitor energy use and evaluate the impact of the energy initiative can take the data they need to Microsoft® Excel® reports with PI DataLink. Standard interactive reports can be created with tools such as Microsoft PowerBI or SQL Server Reporting Services, and data can be fed to these reports / tools with PI Integrator for Business Analytics. To provide real-time visibility to your energy panorama, energy monitoring panels or process indicators can be created in PI Vision ™; so that your users can be used as a phone, tablet or computer on any platform. These display panels / screens can transmit in the form of information, in a graphical form that facilitates information and shaping.\r\n\r\n\r\nEnerji kullanımını izlemek ve enerji girişiminin etkisini değerlendirmek için haftalık veya aylık raporlar üretmesi gereken kullanıcılar, ihtiyaç duydukları verileri PI DataLink ile Microsoft® Excel® raporlarına götürebilirler.\r\nMicrosoft PowerBI veya SQL Server Raporlama Servisleri gibi araçlarla standart etkileşimli raporlar oluşturulabilir ve veriler PI Integrator for Business Analytics ile bu raporlara / araçlara beslenebilir.\r\nEnerji manzaranıza gerçek zamanlı görünürlük sağlamak için PI Vision ™ ‘da enerji gösterge panoları veya işlem göstergeleri oluşturulabilir; bu sayede kullanıcılarınız herhangi bir platformda bir telefon, tablet veya bilgisayar olarak kullanılabilir. Bu gösterge panoları / ekranları, bir bilgi biçiminde, bilgi ve şekil vermeyi kolaylaştıran bir grafik biçiminde iletebilir.\r\n \r\n\r\n**Benefits of PI System in Energy Sector**\r\nEnergy costs are major operational costs for most industries. Understanding your energy use is very important to process improvement and efficiency, as well as to embrace an energy-conscious culture in your organization. With better visibility in energy use, it is easier to understand how operational practices affect energy consumption. But reducing energy consumption is not only good for the bottom line. And reducing energy consumption can minimize an organization\'s carbon footprint, reduce overall social impacts, and maintain reputation of company as being responsible for environment.\r\nFor example, Anglo American Platinum used the PI System to provide visibility of power consumption and to enable various energy management initiatives. They made the data visible in the organization and achieved 1% reduction in electrical power consumption. This reduction partially provided real-time feedback to end users, allowing them to see the impact of the changes they made in the process. Carnegie Melon University started a project to monitor facilities with PI System and Microsoft Azure Machine Learning. They concluded that they could reduce their energy costs by 20% by implementing their solution. Similarly, MOL Group, an international Oil and Gas company, uses the PI System to produce EnPIs to monitor energy data. They expect 2% reduction of annual steam and fuel gas consumption as well as 20,000 tons / year CO2 reduction, and to have a share of € 3,5 million per year with reduced operational costs.\r\n\r\n\r\nAs a result, any reduction in energy consumption can result in significant savings. Companies in various industries can benefit significantly from energy analysis. The PI System can help your company base on energy consumption, accelerate process improvement, increase efficiency, and provide visibility in impact process solutions on energy initiative objectives. Companies wishing to benefit from the PI System for energy optimization projects can try to adopt the strategies outlined in this presentation by contacting KONTROLMATIK and getting information about AF studies (mail link).', 'blog_posts\\September2019\\EQtQXKeuGiU4FGY6uz73.jpg', 'osisoft-pi-system-monitoring-and-managing-energy-kontrolmatik', 'OSIsoft PI Sistem: Enerjiyi İzlemek ve Yönetmek', 'DRAFT', '0', '2019-09-10 13:32:36', '2020-01-30 06:08:59', 'OSIsoft PI System: Monitoring and Managing Energy', '[\"Nesnelerin \\u0130nterneti\",\"Otomasyon\",\"Technologies\"]', NULL, 'en', ''),
(15, 1, 25, 'technologies', 'OSIsoft PI System: Monitoring and Managing Energy', 'OSIsoft PI System: Monitoring and Managing Energy', 'Energy is one of the largest and most compulsory operational expenses for many organizations. Marginal reductions in energy consumption can significantly affect costs.', '**Energy Management with PI System**\r\n\r\n\r\nEnergy is one of the largest and most compulsory operational expenses for many organizations. Marginal reductions in energy consumption can significantly affect costs. Although many companies embark on energy initiatives, they fail due to lack of visibility in energy consumption, insufficiency of core values, and inability to measure the benefits of energy reduction initiatives. The PI System developed by OSIsoft helps organizations understand their energy networks, basic energy consumption, create Energy Performance Indicators and identify the impacts of energy initiatives. This article summarizes how organizations can use the PI System to capture energy measurements to provide real-time and historical visibility in energy use. This allows you to base the energy use throughout your organization and provides an understanding of the impacts of your energy initiatives.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n**Energy Management and ISO 50001**\r\n\r\nEnergy is a critical component for organizations and potentially a significant operating cost. One of the current standards for energy management is ISO 50001. Many organizations have adopted (or began to adopt) this standard in energy management to reduce energy costs as part of their corporate sustainability initiatives. Compliance with environmental policies or minimizing, the impact of their company on society. An inseparable part of the ISO 50001 standard is to base the energy use, efficiency and consumption, and then determine whether energy performance matches the defined objectives, and to continuously monitor and measure the processes to report the results. The PI System is well suited to help organizations meet these requirements.\r\n\r\n**With the PI System, companies can handle the followings:**\r\n\r\nCollect and consolidate energy data from assets, meters and external systems with an accuracy that provides the visibility required to evaluate energy performance. Create analytics to regulate energy data, and to monitor and measure energy performance. Provide powerful tools to analyze and share energy performance information. PI System information can be presented to users in a variety of ways and shared with other corporate systems. Planning phase of Top Level Solution ISO framework requires an energy audit to measure existing energy performance and identify gaps. This step is crucial for understanding which energy information are available in your organization. In many cases, additional measurement is required to achieve the correct level of detail to meet your energy reduction objectives. However, not performing measurement should not prevent organizations from collecting, modeling of current energy information; and collecting EnPIs for identification. Although this blog does not cover data collection, it should be noted that OSIsoft offers various initiatives and connectors to collect information from SCADA, PLC, DCS, meters, and many other data sources. Understanding energy use on one site and across your organization can add value to your organization, including below:\r\n\r\n*	Reduction of energy through process improvements.\r\n*	Detection of energy increases.\r\n*	Producing EnPIs such as kWh / ton or kWh / product.\r\n*	comparison of specific energy consumption between technologies.\r\n* Comparing the bill counter according to actual and calculated energy usage.\r\n*	Modeling the Energy Performance\r\n*	The first step in designing a model for energy management is to understand the relationships between your equipment / assets, your processing area and your overall organizational hierarchy. For this purpose, organizations can follow ISA 88 